  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention for the child_process module through a multi-layered validation architecture spanning JavaScript and C++ code.\n\n## Core Validation Functions (lib/child_process.js)\n\nThe primary validation functions are implemented in lib/child_process.js:\n\n1. **validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 963-967)**: Checks for null bytes (\\u0000) in individual string arguments. This function prevents null-byte injection attacks by throwing ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if a string contains null bytes.\n\n2. **validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 970-974)**: Iterates through arrays of arguments and applies validateArgumentNullCheck to each element, ensuring all command arguments are free from null-byte injection.\n\n## Argument Normalization Functions\n\nThree normalization functions handle different child_process methods:\n\n1. **normalizeSpawnArguments() (line 538-745)**: Normalizes arguments for spawn(), spawnSync(), and serves as the foundation for exec family. This function:\n   - Validates the file parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 540\n   - Validates all args with validateArgumentsNullCheck() at line 556\n   - Validates shell parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 613\n   - Validates argv0 with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 597\n   - Handles shell command construction with null-byte awareness\n\n2. **normalizeExecArgs() (line 188-206)**: Handles exec() command validation:\n   - Validates the command parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 190\n   - Sets shell to true by default for shell-based execution\n   - Returns normalized file, options, and callback\n\n3. **normalizeExecFileArgs() (line 262-296)**: Handles execFile() argument normalization:\n   - Validates argv0 if provided with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 292\n   - Handles flexible argument passing (args can be options object)\n   - Returns normalized file, args, options, and callback\n\n## Public API Entry Points\n\nThe public APIs in lib/child_process.js implement the validation chain:\n\n1. **exec() (line 231-236)**: Spawns a shell executing a command string\n   - Calls normalizeExecArgs() for validation\n   - Delegates to execFile() for actual spawning\n\n2. **execFile() (line 323-522)**: Spawns a file directly without shell\n   - Calls normalizeExecFileArgs() for argument validation\n   - Calls spawn() with normalized options\n   - Handles stdout/stderr buffering with configurable maxBuffer\n\n3. **spawn() (line 745-791)**: Asynchronous process spawning\n   - Calls normalizeSpawnArguments() for comprehensive argument validation\n   - Validates timeout and signal parameters\n   - Creates a new ChildProcess instance and calls its spawn method\n\n4. **execSync() (line 945-??)**: Synchronous version of exec()\n   - Uses normalizeExecArgs() for command validation\n   - Delegates to internal spawnSync() implementation\n\n5. **execFileSync() (line 907-??)**: Synchronous version of execFile()\n   - Uses normalizeExecFileArgs() for argument validation\n   - Calls normalizeSpawnArguments() for final processing\n\n6. **spawnSync() (line 823-869)**: Synchronous process spawning\n   - Calls normalizeSpawnArguments() with null-byte validation\n   - Validates stdio configuration\n   - Delegates to internal C++ spawnSync() implementation\n\n7. **fork() (line 122-172)**: Specialized spawning for Node.js child processes\n   - Validates execPath with validateArgumentNullCheck() at line 142\n   - Validates execArgv array with validateArgumentsNullCheck() at line 146\n   - Calls spawn() with validated options\n\n## JavaScript-to-C++ Interface (lib/internal/child_process.js)\n\n**ChildProcess class and spawn method (line 254-479)**:\n- Line 266: Creates internal native handle: `this._handle = new Process()`\n- Line 395: Calls native spawn: `const err = this._handle.spawn(options)`\n- The spawn method validates options structure and validates the file and args before passing to C++\n- Line 385: Validates file parameter\n- Line 391: Validates args array\n- Interfaces with ProcessWrap through the Process native binding\n\n## C++ Native Bindings\n\n**src/process_wrap.cc**:\n- **ProcessWrap class (line 51-??)**: C++ class implementing the native process binding\n  - Line 91-95: Constructor that wraps a libuv process handle\n  - Lines 65-66: Registers spawn and kill methods with V8\n  - Line 153-327: **ProcessWrap::Spawn() method** - Performs final C++ level validation and spawning\n    - Line 158-159: Permission check for child_process execution\n    - Line 193-197: Extracts and validates the file path from options\n    - Line 110-151: ParseStdioOptions() - Parses and validates stdio configuration\n    - Interfaces with libuv (uv_spawn) for actual process creation\n\n**src/spawn_sync.cc**:\n- Implements synchronous process spawning with the same validation principles\n- Line 22-28: Includes necessary headers\n- Provides SyncProcessRunner and related classes for blocking process execution\n- Contains validation equivalent to async ProcessWrap::Spawn()\n\n## Validation Chain Summary\n\nThe complete command injection prevention chain flows as follows:\n\n1. **User API Call** → spawn(), exec(), execFile(), fork()\n   ↓\n2. **Normalization** → normalizeSpawnArguments(), normalizeExecArgs(), normalizeExecFileArgs()\n   ↓\n3. **Null-Byte Validation** → validateArgumentNullCheck(), validateArgumentsNullCheck()\n   ↓\n4. **ChildProcess Instance** → new ChildProcess() in lib/child_process.js\n   ↓\n5. **JavaScript-C++ Bridge** → ChildProcess.prototype.spawn() in lib/internal/child_process.js\n   ↓\n6. **Native C++ Execution** → ProcessWrap::Spawn() in src/process_wrap.cc or sync equivalent in src/spawn_sync.cc\n   ↓\n7. **System Call** → libuv/OS process creation\n\nThis architecture ensures that command injection attacks through null bytes, shell metacharacters (in shell:false mode), and environment variable manipulation are prevented at multiple layers before